    "dailyBrief": {
        "brent": 93.97,
        "brentDeltaPct": 2.7,
        "bullets": [
            "Trump threatened to destroy an Iranian bridge or power plant for every ship attacked in the Strait of Hormuz, per gCaptain.",
            "Brent crude rose +2.70% over 24 hours to $93.97 at 14:52 UTC, reaching its highest level since mid-June.",
            "Crisis Pressure sits in the extreme band, rising, while 450 vessels were anchored or stopped as of 14:52 UTC."
        ],
        "date": "2026-07-22",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-22T14:52:24.818Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "The Strait of Hormuz is operating under acute stress, with the Hormuz Index Crisis Pressure composite in the extreme band and continuing to rise, driven primarily by physical transit deviation. President Trump announced a retaliatory framework on Wednesday, warning that the United States would destroy one Iranian bridge or power plant for each ship attacked in the strait, per gCaptain; multiple other outlets, all currently unverified or single-source, are carrying similar characterizations of the statement. That policy signal pushed Brent to $93.97 at 14:52 UTC, a +2.70% gain over 24 hours. The most recent IMF PortWatch published transit count, for 2026-07-19, stood at 15 vessels against a pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day; PortWatch publishes on a weekly Tuesday cycle, so a multi-day lag is expected. Separately, port arrivals across the Hormuz-area ports in the most recent 24 hours reached 263 vessels, a figure drawn from a different methodology and not comparable to the PortWatch transit count. At 14:52 UTC, 450 vessels were anchored or stopped in the region. The Escalation Forecast composite sits in the elevated band and has been flat over the past 24 hours, with Polymarket escalation contracts as the top contributor; the divergence between an extreme and rising state reading and a flat elevated forecast suggests markets are pricing uncertainty without yet committing to a breakout scenario.",
